  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Working to Improve Sexual and Reproductive Health Emergency Response (WISER)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Following the track record of significant impact that has been achieved with support from the Health Sector and The Nigeria Humanitarian Fund (NHF) since 2017, Action Health Incorporated (AHI) seeks to continue the provision of life-saving assistance and alleviate suffering through the provision of integrated primary health care services and coordinated humanitarian response with specific focus on emergency sexual and reproductive health care services at the facility and community level in addition to the provision of essential drugs and medical supplies for IDP&apos;s with critical needs in accordance with the 2019-2021 Humanitarian Response Strategy. 

In a bid to scale up and maintain a continuum of care for beneficiaries of AHI sexual and reproductive health intervention funded through the NHF 2019 first reserve allocation, the Working to Improve Sexual and Reproductive Health Emergency Response (WISER) project will focus on utilizing existing human resources and  strengthen health systems to provide urgent Sexual and Reproductive Health (SRH) services in two Local Government Areas namely Dikwa and Monguno LGA within Borno State which still experiences critical gaps, Including the influx of IDP&apos;s and Returnees with limited access to optimum health care services and the high costs of quality medicine.

At the end of the project cycle, this project scale up aims to reduce maternal amp infant mortality and morbidity in the two identified LGA&apos;s with urgent need of live saving interventions. This goal will be achieved through the provision of life saving drugs, engaging qualified health care service providers for the provision of quality sexual and reproductive health services, establishment of an information center, provide family planning services, Disseminate SRH Key messages and revive the Emergency Transport Scheme in collaboration with the National Union of Road Transport Workers (NURTW) to transport women to tertiary health centers free of charge or at minimal cost when they are faced with health complications.  

The WISER project will also incorporate monitoring, evaluation, accountability and learning structures to inform strategies for current and future interventions.

A detailed implementation plan is provided in the grant request justification section.</narrative>
  </description>
